Option 1 (Recommended): Use an IAM User for local access

Create an IAM user (e.g. harsh).
Generate an Access Key.
Configure your AWS CLI:
aws configure
Grant that IAM user access to your EKS cluster.

If your cluster uses EKS Access Entries:

aws eks create-access-entry \
  --cluster-name end-to-end-devops-dev-eks \
  --principal-arn arn:aws:iam::198452822403:user/harsh

Then:

aws eks associate-access-policy \
  --cluster-name end-to-end-devops-dev-eks \
  --principal-arn arn:aws:iam::198452822403:user/harsh \
  --policy-arn arn:aws:eks::aws:cluster-access-policy/AmazonEKSClusterAdminPolicy \
  --access-scope type=cluster



Option 2: Allow an IAM user to assume the GitHub role

If you want to use the same end-to-end-devops role from your laptop, you'll need to:

create an IAM user,
give it permission to call sts:AssumeRole,
modify the end-to-end-devops role's trust policy to trust both:
GitHub OIDC, and
your IAM user.

Then you can run:

aws sts assume-role \
  --role-arn arn:aws:iam::198452822403:role/end-to-end-devops \
  --role-session-name local-session

